1
00:00:00,908 --> 00:00:30,577
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

2
00:00:33,832 --> 00:00:43,625
So for those of you who have just joined us, I've been using the story of the Buddha as a sort of platform to talk about the Dhamma.

3
00:00:46,310 --> 00:00:57,325
So the first talk was about him before he was born, in his previous lives, and we talked about it all the way up to the point where he was leaving home.

4
00:01:07,361 --> 00:01:36,492
and there's one thing I just wanted to revise as it were was the part of the great renunciation when remember what's thrown him out of the good life was getting fed up with pleasure and there was a thought occurred to me that we often get confused between boredom and dispassion or

5
00:01:37,382 --> 00:01:40,927
disenchantment, disinterest, a spiritual state.

6
00:01:42,751 --> 00:01:45,433
And it occurs to me that the real difference is this.

7
00:01:46,555 --> 00:01:59,072
When we get bored with something, and then we, as it were, go on a diet or a fast, after not too long a time, we get the craving come back up again for the same old thing.

8
00:02:00,596 --> 00:02:05,162
So that's not the feeling of

9
00:02:07,117 --> 00:02:34,609
disinterest that comes when as it were a part of us has truly had enough of something so even though it's placed before us and time has passed there's nothing drawing us to that old pleasure and that would definitely suggest that it's a movement in the heart moving away from the sensual life so when we

10
00:02:35,027 --> 00:03:04,241
refer back to the disgust he felt after the party when they're all hanging about looking terrible um if we stress the disgust i think we're slightly off the point it was it was the fact that it wasn't there was no drawing towards it again there was no there was no pleasure to be had there no happiness to be had there and on top of that remember there were the four signs the messengers of the gods uh you know the sick the the um

11
00:03:04,762 --> 00:03:09,931
A very aged person, the corpse, and the person sitting under a tree in some of the stories.

12
00:03:10,853 --> 00:03:12,254
And then he makes the great renunciation.

13
00:03:12,276 --> 00:03:12,635
He leaves.

14
00:03:13,016 --> 00:03:22,152
And I don't know whether I said this last time, but there's that lovely little bit where he peeps in and sees his newly born son with his wife.

15
00:03:22,774 --> 00:03:27,562
And he doesn't go towards them because that would again bring up all his doubts.

16
00:03:28,521 --> 00:03:34,591
And that gives a sort of human touch to what seems to be like desertion.

17
00:03:36,734 --> 00:03:41,180
But he was just empowered to go.

18
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:47,489
I mean, there are many times, aren't there, when people are called away from the family life in war, stuff like that.

19
00:03:48,390 --> 00:03:52,757
In fact, when I was thinking about this, I remembered...

20
00:03:53,108 --> 00:04:05,937
Somewhere in the 80s, the British government decided to position American missiles in Greenham Common, and there was a huge sort of uproar about that from a certain section of the population.

21
00:04:06,354 --> 00:04:07,956
And it was taken over by women.

22
00:04:08,197 --> 00:04:10,579
It became an encampment for women.

23
00:04:10,598 --> 00:04:13,040
And I remember this for two years, some of them were.

24
00:04:13,502 --> 00:04:18,807
And I remember this one woman being interviewed, and she'd left a family, a young family.

25
00:04:18,966 --> 00:04:21,048
Not very young, they were 10, 12, 13.

26
00:04:21,829 --> 00:04:26,574
So there are times when, as it were, things are even more important than our families.

27
00:04:27,055 --> 00:04:32,160
So for the Buddha, or the Bodhisattva as he was then, there's that drawing, there's that, you know,

28
00:04:32,478 --> 00:04:38,845
And there may be times in our lives when we get that feeling of wanting to go deeper into the practice, you see.

29
00:04:39,565 --> 00:04:41,627
So we have to honor that as best we can.

30
00:04:49,677 --> 00:05:01,050
When I was in Sri Lanka there was a young girl who would tell her father that in the evening whenever he went to bed she would

31
00:05:01,401 --> 00:05:29,990
go up to the day around and in the day around there were shrines where the border and other hats would appear and get teaching and that she a who got that and write the story the border she actually was collecting notes for the book on the border and the father of course would humor another would you may say and she was she was she wasn't six or seven she was eight nine ten

32
00:05:30,747 --> 00:05:35,855
I think it was 10 when she came to our monastery.

33
00:05:35,875 --> 00:05:38,819
And she got fed up with her parents sort of not believing her.

34
00:05:39,339 --> 00:05:42,245
So one night she said to them, I'm off now.

35
00:05:42,886 --> 00:05:47,173
And right there before the very eyes, she rose up and disappeared.

36
00:05:49,937 --> 00:05:52,440
And the father and mother then thought, this is very strange.

37
00:05:52,461 --> 00:05:56,447
So when she reappeared, they went visiting monasteries with her.

38
00:05:56,466 --> 00:05:58,290
And they ended up at Kandabodha.

39
00:05:58,961 --> 00:06:03,507
And I wasn't there for the interview, but I heard the little cassette that they made of the interview.

40
00:06:05,028 --> 00:06:08,934
And she said exactly what I said to you.

41
00:06:08,954 --> 00:06:11,497
And she wouldn't bow to monks because she was an Arahant.

42
00:06:12,637 --> 00:06:16,963
And when they asked her about what meditation was, she seemed to know what it was.

43
00:06:17,043 --> 00:06:19,565
There was no problem there.

44
00:06:19,586 --> 00:06:22,310
And she said she'd come down really to look after her grandfather.

45
00:06:22,329 --> 00:06:24,471
That's why she'd taken rebirth.

46
00:06:24,492 --> 00:06:28,497
But the reason I mention it is that in this book she was writing, the Buddha...

47
00:06:29,016 --> 00:06:39,312
turned back six times before he finally made the decision to cross the Rubicon and make the big detachment bit.

48
00:06:39,331 --> 00:06:53,232
So this is where, you know, when you read the scriptures, you always get this coming in of what we might call the supernatural, that which is above what we would consider to be nature.

49
00:06:54,074 --> 00:06:56,416
And these days, of course, we tend to poo-poo all that.

50
00:06:56,437 --> 00:06:57,858
There's a load of...

51
00:06:58,312 --> 00:07:27,778
but unfortunately it is right there within the scriptures so that's just to really just to contemplate that the spiritual life does ask us to renounce things that we truly love it can be very difficult but once that seed is within you once you know you've got to go then you've got to go

52
00:07:30,036 --> 00:07:35,745
So now he's left and he's cut his hair off and his horse has died from sheer grief.

53
00:07:36,447 --> 00:07:37,247
Poor old Kantaka.

54
00:07:38,430 --> 00:07:44,158
And he's put on the rag robes and he goes off to his first two teachers, two yoga teachers.

55
00:07:45,560 --> 00:07:47,923
Alara Kalama and Udaka Ramaputa.

56
00:07:48,865 --> 00:07:53,192
And remember that his big quest is, is there an end to suffering?

57
00:07:53,252 --> 00:07:54,934
Is there an end to unsatisfactoriness?

58
00:07:54,954 --> 00:07:56,196
Or is there...

59
00:07:57,120 --> 00:08:02,783
You know, is there an answer to the reason why we're conscious and why we should be suffering because we're conscious?

60
00:08:04,408 --> 00:08:08,463
And both of these train him in what we now call the jhanas.

61
00:08:08,831 --> 00:08:17,023
So the first person, Aracalama, took him up to the third Arupajana, and Uddhaka Ramaputa took him to the end.

62
00:08:17,184 --> 00:08:21,810
So he did the four Arupajanas and the four Arupajanas.

63
00:08:21,829 --> 00:08:34,047
And on both occasions, they were so taken by his adeptness at entering and re-entering these jhanas that they both said that he was their equal and would he come and teach with them.

64
00:08:34,955 --> 00:08:39,418
And on both occasions, he, of course, says no.

65
00:08:40,100 --> 00:08:42,682
He doesn't really answer his problem.

66
00:08:43,722 --> 00:08:47,606
So what is it about the jhanas that doesn't answer the problem of suffering?

67
00:08:48,707 --> 00:08:53,292
So remember that when we practice jhana, and it's becoming more fashionable.

68
00:08:53,371 --> 00:08:56,554
When I came into Buddhism, it was no-no.

69
00:08:57,696 --> 00:08:59,677
You didn't do things like that.

70
00:08:59,697 --> 00:09:03,881
The Zen school that I was in called it ghetto Zen, bad, bad Zen.

71
00:09:04,789 --> 00:09:10,480
And everybody else from Ajahn Sumedho right through to the Mahasi sort of put you off it.

72
00:09:11,142 --> 00:09:16,974
But these days it's sort of coming in with, I think, the work of Lee Brassington and especially perhaps Upa Auk.

73
00:09:18,296 --> 00:09:25,971
So what is it about the jhanas which make some schools avoid it?

74
00:09:27,975 --> 00:09:34,845
It's because, remember, that the jhanas are about creating a state of mind, just as we do when we see a good film or have a good meal.

75
00:09:35,946 --> 00:09:40,873
You're trying to create a beautiful environment within ourselves.

76
00:09:41,273 --> 00:09:41,974
That's what it's about.

77
00:09:42,934 --> 00:09:44,496
Because that's where the pain is.

78
00:09:45,177 --> 00:09:46,139
That's where the suffering is.

79
00:09:46,178 --> 00:09:46,899
It's inside us.

80
00:09:47,301 --> 00:09:49,543
So we seek pleasure often.

81
00:09:49,783 --> 00:09:55,130
We seek distraction often in order just to get away from the pain inside us.

82
00:09:55,717 --> 00:10:02,787
Even here in our meditation we might find ourselves walking just because we just don't want to sit anymore, it's too painful.

83
00:10:02,807 --> 00:10:06,672
So even little small things can be little distractions for us.

84
00:10:07,533 --> 00:10:14,701
So the jhana of course are just developing a state of mind and there are many ways that you can do it.

85
00:10:15,964 --> 00:10:24,595
And why is it that it can be such a path which can take you away

86
00:10:25,115 --> 00:10:26,177
from the practice.

87
00:10:27,418 --> 00:10:37,619
And that's because when a person is truly adept at the jhanas, when he can just turn it on, when they can just turn it on, it stays with them all day.

88
00:10:38,440 --> 00:10:44,270
It's not that they go into that depth absorption, but the mental state stays with them all day.

89
00:10:45,347 --> 00:10:56,019
So that the teacher of a jhana knows when the student is becoming adept, when even if you were to pull their ears and box them around the nose, they're still very happy.

90
00:10:56,340 --> 00:11:00,465
They're not touched by it because their heart's gleaming with happiness and joy.

91
00:11:01,765 --> 00:11:11,397
And it's that sort of telltale sign that the mind, now the citta, or perhaps just the heart and mind, are being lifted up to that level.

92
00:11:12,437 --> 00:11:14,139
Now,

93
00:11:14,542 --> 00:11:18,909
People in ordinary daily life might do that on a slightly different level.

94
00:11:19,451 --> 00:11:24,801
So, for instance, somebody who is tremendously interested in what they're doing.

95
00:11:25,442 --> 00:11:31,212
So their lives are empowered by that interest or empowered by being in power.

96
00:11:32,054 --> 00:11:36,903
Or business people who have this goal and are driving themselves towards it.

97
00:11:37,340 --> 00:11:46,429
can usually often just lift themselves to that level of energy and commitment whereby they never drop until, of course, the business fails.

98
00:11:47,331 --> 00:11:48,293
And then they drop.

99
00:11:50,115 --> 00:11:52,297
And that really is the point of the jhana.

100
00:11:52,957 --> 00:11:59,144
So when the jhanas go down, then, of course, what comes up is the same old Siddhartha Gautama.

101
00:11:59,732 --> 00:12:17,818
And that's what he discovered, that while he was in this state and could maintain it, actually he hadn't rooted out some of his emotional problems, but deeply he could see that when you come out of that, then you're back to where you were.

102
00:12:19,100 --> 00:12:29,436
So with that disappointment, I mean it must have been disappointing for him, we can presume that as a layperson,

103
00:12:29,990 --> 00:12:53,398
at you know in the in the palace that he had explored all these things both theoretically with the Brahmins and people like that and that now he was into the practice and that this was the practice that everybody was saying you know this is this is where it's at and the idea remember of the jhana wasn't simply to feel happy now it was that when you're reborn you get reborn in the jhana realm

104
00:12:53,833 --> 00:12:57,557
and they last for eons upon eons, endless times.

105
00:12:58,178 --> 00:13:11,573
So the idea is that, you know, as you go up the jhana scale, and you enter into the lower heavenly realms, then into the arupa realms, and finally into the great big brahma realms, where you can hang about for a heck of a long time.

106
00:13:11,634 --> 00:13:18,761
But then, of course, it drops, but because of your good karma, you probably only drop to being a human being, where you do the jhanas again, sort of rev them up,

107
00:13:19,230 --> 00:13:47,398
and you go back up again so in terms of if you remember the way that people would think in those days of this constant round of birth and rebirth at least that seemed to be a viable answer it was much happier up there in those realms than it is in this one so anyway he's disappointed with that and the next thing he does of course is he goes off to practice these mortifications

108
00:13:48,475 --> 00:14:00,572
Now, I've never been able to really find what was the understanding behind the mortifications.

109
00:14:01,253 --> 00:14:14,009
I've tried to look at it, but the only reason I can think of, which is really taken also from the Christian tradition, is that the reason why we're unhappy is because of the body.

110
00:14:14,850 --> 00:14:17,875
It's the body that lets in images.

111
00:14:18,056 --> 00:14:19,798
It's the body that has greed.

112
00:14:19,857 --> 00:14:21,341
It's the body that has lust.

113
00:14:22,341 --> 00:14:23,384
We feel it in the body.

114
00:14:23,864 --> 00:14:28,812
So if we can somehow control the body, then this would liberate the mind.

115
00:14:30,134 --> 00:14:35,201
So all these things that the Buddha did, you know, he said he starved himself.

116
00:14:35,400 --> 00:14:39,668
Well, you know, he was down to a grain of oats or something every day.

117
00:14:40,469 --> 00:14:44,014
And he got to the point where he could hold his spine through his stomach

118
00:14:45,006 --> 00:15:02,105
and that sort of very fierce asceticism, really I think was based on that understanding that if you reduce the appetite to the body, then somehow the mind is liberated, the citta is liberated.

119
00:15:03,866 --> 00:15:10,474
Now for those of you, I'm sure all of you, have done a 10-day fast or longer, a month fast,

120
00:15:10,893 --> 00:15:15,216
you'll know that the first three days are absolutely horrible while the body's clearing out its rubbish.

121
00:15:15,898 --> 00:15:20,322
But then after that, you do enter into this very clear, very easy state.

122
00:15:20,642 --> 00:15:24,686
And of course, no feelings of hunger because the body's eating itself.

123
00:15:26,488 --> 00:15:33,033
So, in that clarity, it's much easier to do certain practices.

124
00:15:34,215 --> 00:15:40,461
And I've always presumed that that's what self-mortification is about.

125
00:15:40,626 --> 00:15:49,666
Interestingly enough, the whole practice, if you look at the words, is actually about self-mortification, about the destruction of self.

126
00:15:50,187 --> 00:15:56,981
But here we're using it in that old form of some form of controlling the body.

127
00:15:58,868 --> 00:16:15,245
But for whatever reasons there were, and remember that some of them came from the other leader who was a contemporary elder of the Buddha, the Jain leader, who was definitely into these sorts of things.

128
00:16:16,267 --> 00:16:18,750
Of course, his idea rested on karma.

129
00:16:18,889 --> 00:16:24,115
His idea was that as soon as you do an action, you're creating more sankharas.

130
00:16:24,216 --> 00:16:25,977
So you've got to stop doing.

131
00:16:26,379 --> 00:16:27,659
You've got to stop doing.

132
00:16:28,197 --> 00:16:31,481
So eventually the Jain saint starves themselves to death.

133
00:16:31,562 --> 00:16:33,664
That's the Jain way of doing things.

134
00:16:36,690 --> 00:16:42,658
And there's a presumption that the Buddha followed that a little bit just to find out what all that was about.

135
00:16:44,140 --> 00:16:52,293
But eventually, as you know, he ends up being very disconsolate and he just says it was just painful, that's all.

136
00:16:53,815 --> 00:16:56,178
He didn't seem to achieve anything at all.

137
00:16:57,442 --> 00:17:00,785
So now we can imagine him coming to a point of despair.

138
00:17:01,727 --> 00:17:10,479
So he's taken everything that the society has given him in his search and it just seems to have come to a dead end.

139
00:17:14,443 --> 00:17:26,200
In the story, of course, he's sitting on the roadside when a woman, Sujata, comes along with a bowl of offering for the gods.

140
00:17:26,855 --> 00:17:36,685
She's going towards the shrine, and she sees him, and scriptures are, you know, these apocryphal tales will be what they are.

141
00:17:37,287 --> 00:17:41,352
And, of course, she sees a god sitting by the road, a deva, and she honors him.

142
00:17:41,972 --> 00:17:45,416
But, frankly, he must have looked pretty ragged and pretty awful.

143
00:17:46,377 --> 00:17:51,022
And as she's walking by, she must have thought, oh, this poor ascetic probably needs my rice pudding.

144
00:17:52,234 --> 00:18:00,144
So she offers this rice pudding and somebody actually corrected me and said that that was a British Raj invention.

145
00:18:00,324 --> 00:18:01,684
That is, there was no rice pudding.

146
00:18:03,567 --> 00:18:08,653
What there was, was a rice cake, which they have in Sri Lanka called Kiribat.

147
00:18:09,433 --> 00:18:18,022
And it's basically rice boiled in coconut milk, which is then boiled out and it's patted out and it's made a little block.

148
00:18:19,048 --> 00:18:24,776
Now, of course, if I had a choice, if I was in the Buddha's position there and had a choice, I'd definitely go for the British variety.

149
00:18:25,737 --> 00:18:30,903
And the reason for that isn't just facetious.

150
00:18:31,663 --> 00:18:39,093
It's because as he's eating this, or at some point close to that time, he remembers this point in childhood.

151
00:18:41,214 --> 00:18:45,359
And what he remembers is watching his father eat.

152
00:18:45,846 --> 00:18:49,009
opening up the plying season by doing some sort of plying ceremony.

153
00:18:51,093 --> 00:19:00,682
And there's something about that watching, there's something about the way he's looking which gives him an inspiration.

154
00:19:01,963 --> 00:19:09,913
Somehow he remembers being in a state, to use that word, which is different in quality

155
00:19:10,383 --> 00:19:16,588
to all the jhanas he's done and all the states that might have come up when he was doing the self-mortification.

156
00:19:19,510 --> 00:19:33,284
And I was walking through Birmingham Station in Britain and as I was going up the escalator to the shopping mall, there was a great big poster up there with different pictures on it.

157
00:19:34,203 --> 00:19:40,390
And there was one picture which, as soon as I saw it, I almost shouted with glee,

158
00:19:40,740 --> 00:19:44,324
And before they took me away, I was able to take a picture.

159
00:19:45,465 --> 00:19:49,088
And this little picture is what I call Satipanya.

160
00:19:49,769 --> 00:20:01,020
And I think it's the closest thing I've seen as an image to that state of mind which arises, shall we say, either just before or just upon the seeing.

161
00:20:08,086 --> 00:20:09,769
And this little baby...

162
00:20:10,288 --> 00:20:19,384
You see, all those eyes are completely open, completely absorbed in what... Well, you can't tell it's a she or he, you see.

163
00:20:19,404 --> 00:20:21,087
That's the other thing about Satyapanya, isn't it?

164
00:20:21,167 --> 00:20:23,392
It's not been diversified.

165
00:20:23,412 --> 00:20:24,855
And, of course, the mouth has dropped.

166
00:20:25,882 --> 00:20:40,203
Now, that relaxed jaw is a great sign to us that the thinking mind has stopped, because the connection between the tongue and the jaw is intimate.

167
00:20:40,704 --> 00:20:46,012
You may have seen that when you're thinking, there are these little vibrations on the tongue.

168
00:20:46,855 --> 00:20:48,257
It's already ready to move.

169
00:20:49,578 --> 00:20:50,319
And

170
00:20:51,615 --> 00:21:00,403
As children, you know, we have that, just that very simple capacity, especially, you know, until around about the age of six, seven, of just being able to look.

171
00:21:01,704 --> 00:21:12,074
And I'm sure you had the bad experiences I had of having looked like that and your parents tell you to shut your mouth because you look gormless.

172
00:21:14,675 --> 00:21:20,121
And after that, you never look the same, which is very unfortunate.

173
00:21:20,522 --> 00:21:26,035
So if you ever see a child looking like that, you have to stop very still while the child's absorbed it.

174
00:21:26,375 --> 00:21:35,095
And if you see a child doing that, there's a moment of complete silence, you see, and then suddenly the question, what is it?

175
00:21:36,578 --> 00:21:39,003
But it has to be absorbed first.

176
00:21:40,839 --> 00:21:44,003
So, this quality of satipaṇya.

177
00:21:44,023 --> 00:21:47,909
Now, in the jhanas, there's sati, awareness.

178
00:21:48,009 --> 00:21:50,413
In fact, I mean, right awareness.

179
00:21:50,452 --> 00:21:52,515
Well, it's awareness, shall we say.

180
00:21:53,316 --> 00:21:54,837
Awareness never leaves us.

181
00:21:54,857 --> 00:21:55,940
It's there when we're asleep.

182
00:21:55,960 --> 00:21:57,862
I mean, something turns us over.

183
00:21:58,702 --> 00:22:00,806
Something pulls the blanket over us when we're cold.

184
00:22:01,366 --> 00:22:05,071
So, it's not as though awareness goes or disappears completely.

185
00:22:05,092 --> 00:22:06,814
It's always there in some way.

186
00:22:07,384 --> 00:22:15,355
And when somebody practices jhāna, awareness is there, that's not the problem, you see.

187
00:22:15,777 --> 00:22:25,730
But it's this other quality that was missing, this paññā, this jñāna, this intuitive intelligence, that question mark.

188
00:22:25,750 --> 00:22:29,455
And that question mark is talked about in Zen as the great doubt.

189
00:22:30,396 --> 00:22:34,122
Not meaning that you're doubting the practice, but that wanting to know.

190
00:22:34,142 --> 00:22:34,843
Hmm?

191
00:22:36,325 --> 00:23:01,759
so that's what he remembers that's what he remembers so now so you know this brings also to mind the importance of food so keep that in mind so now having made a distout really sort of enlivened by that now he's got a new tack a new something to follow

192
00:23:02,278 --> 00:23:08,488
he goes to find this place near the river Naranjana where he's going to find a place to sit.

193
00:23:09,650 --> 00:23:17,221
And again, one of these lovely little apocryphal stories, he puts his bowl into the river and it goes upwards.

194
00:23:18,523 --> 00:23:19,726
And it goes against the flow.

195
00:23:20,165 --> 00:23:26,615
And for those of you who come to my little morning tip, I pointed out that I once got a card which

196
00:23:27,018 --> 00:23:43,086
which had a dead fish flowing in the river and the title was only dead fish go with the flow so if you think of this magical moment which is representative of the fact that

197
00:23:43,775 --> 00:23:47,461
the Dhamma will always go against our conditioning, the self-conditioning.

198
00:23:47,480 --> 00:23:51,247
So it's always an uphill struggle, right?

199
00:23:51,448 --> 00:23:52,849
Small lesser, you don't want to fight it.

200
00:23:53,411 --> 00:23:57,417
But you've got to go up, you've got to go against the conditioning all the time.

201
00:23:58,599 --> 00:24:07,233
And I'll try and spend a bit of time on one of these talks, just revising some of the hindrances.

202
00:24:12,007 --> 00:24:18,175
So now he's found himself a seat and he makes this wonderful great determination.

203
00:24:19,458 --> 00:24:38,086
And in the scriptures it's let my skin, bones and sinews remain and only and let the flesh and blood in my body dry up but not until I attain the supreme enlightenment will I give up this seat of meditation.

204
00:24:39,910 --> 00:24:40,730
Have you tried that?

205
00:24:45,824 --> 00:24:46,585
You can give it a go.

206
00:24:46,704 --> 00:24:49,127
It's sort of humiliating, but it's worth doing it.

207
00:24:50,670 --> 00:24:58,798
Because then you see that to be able to make that sort of determination, he's really built up that determination and power.

208
00:24:58,898 --> 00:25:01,682
I mean, resolution, forbearance, and all that sort of stuff.

209
00:25:02,983 --> 00:25:10,471
And in fact, you might say that he's come to a point where either he finds the answer to this, or he may as well not hang about.

210
00:25:10,491 --> 00:25:11,272
He may as well die.

211
00:25:11,413 --> 00:25:12,034
What's the point?

212
00:25:13,516 --> 00:25:17,441
So at this point, of course, he gets the attack of Mara.

213
00:25:17,800 --> 00:25:21,566
And this book is the story of Gautama Buddha.

214
00:25:21,586 --> 00:25:25,069
It's from the Nidana, the Jatakas.

215
00:25:25,089 --> 00:25:38,886
And I thought I'd read out this lovely battle so that you get the way that these stories build up in that sort of metaphysical, that supernatural way.

216
00:25:40,648 --> 00:25:42,290
So we've lost a lot of this in our

217
00:25:42,692 --> 00:25:45,777
over rational culture, but it's a lovely scene.

218
00:25:45,797 --> 00:25:47,439
So Mara has come.

219
00:25:47,558 --> 00:25:48,921
He's a devaputra.

220
00:25:48,941 --> 00:25:50,163
He's the son of the gods.

221
00:25:50,583 --> 00:25:52,224
He's not a devil from the hellish realm.

222
00:25:52,546 --> 00:25:54,688
He's somebody who entices people.

223
00:25:55,769 --> 00:25:57,852
It's like the Satan in Islam.

224
00:25:59,314 --> 00:26:06,202
When Ayatollah Khomeini called America Satan,

225
00:26:06,182 --> 00:26:10,367
He wasn't thinking of it as an evil, as a Christian devil.

226
00:26:10,488 --> 00:26:17,656
He was thinking of it as that which entices you away from the way of Allah.

227
00:26:19,440 --> 00:26:23,484
So now he's come with all his armies, you see.

228
00:26:25,166 --> 00:26:26,048
And

229
00:26:26,685 --> 00:26:34,300
He's about now, he's really wide up and he's going to attack the Buddha and get him off the seat because he shouldn't be there.

230
00:26:34,361 --> 00:26:35,202
Mara should be there.

231
00:26:35,343 --> 00:26:37,446
The world is about the sensual world.

232
00:26:37,507 --> 00:26:39,191
It's not about getting enlightened.

233
00:26:39,751 --> 00:26:40,874
He's in the wrong seat.

234
00:26:43,278 --> 00:26:49,150
So then the Devaputta Mara raised a tornado wishing to drive away Siddhartha with it.

235
00:26:49,837 --> 00:27:16,217
instantaneously such gales rose from the east and other directions as would have shattered to bits mountain peaks of the height of half a yojana two yojana or three yojana and could have uprooted shrubs and trees of the forest and could have reduced to fragments the villages and townships of the neighborhood but by the virtue and majesty of the great being they lost their force and on reaching the bodhisattva they were not able to shake even the hem of his robe

236
00:27:18,491 --> 00:27:22,777
Wishing to engulf him in water and slay him, he next caused a heavy downpour of rain.

237
00:27:23,738 --> 00:27:29,763
By his great miraculous power, clouds gathered in hundreds of thousands, layer upon layer, and poured forth rain.

238
00:27:30,384 --> 00:27:33,468
The earth was hollowed out by the violence of the torrential downpour.

239
00:27:34,288 --> 00:27:44,279
A great flood came, submerging the treetops of the forest, but it could not moisten his robe, even to the extent of the little space on which a dewdrop could fall.

240
00:27:46,066 --> 00:27:48,147
Next he raised a great shower of rocks.

241
00:27:48,607 --> 00:27:52,852
Large mountain peaks came swirling through the air, issuing smoke and flames.

242
00:27:53,452 --> 00:27:58,518
But on reaching the Bodhisattva, they turned into wreaths of heavenly garlands.

243
00:28:00,920 --> 00:28:02,701
Next he raised a storm of missiles.

244
00:28:03,182 --> 00:28:08,826
Swords, daggers, darts and other weapons, single-edged and double-edged, came hurtling through the sky, smoking and flaming.

245
00:28:09,147 --> 00:28:13,811
But on reaching the Bodhisattva, they turned into heavenly flowers.

246
00:28:15,984 --> 00:28:29,380
Next he raised a shower of burning coals, embers of the ewe of Kimsika flowers came flying through the sky and were scattered at the feet of the Bodhisattva, turning into heavenly flowers.

247
00:28:29,400 --> 00:28:39,951
Next he raised a storm of ashes, red-hot ashes, glowing like fire, came flying through the air, fell at the feet of the Bodhisattva and turned into sandalwood powder.

248
00:28:41,702 --> 00:28:42,964
Next he raised a sandstorm.

249
00:28:43,005 --> 00:28:51,957
Fine particles of sand came smoking and flaming through the sky, fell at the feet of the Bodhisattva and turned into heavenly flowers.

250
00:28:54,259 --> 00:28:55,962
Next he raised a storm of mud.

251
00:28:56,022 --> 00:29:03,472
The mud came smoking and flaming through the air, fell at the feet of the Bodhisattva and turned into heavenly ointments.

252
00:29:05,415 --> 00:29:10,883
He next created a gloom which was as thick as when four conditions are found in combination.

253
00:29:11,317 --> 00:29:20,529
And on reaching the Bodhisattva, it disappeared as darkness that vanishes with the oncoming radiance of the sun.

254
00:29:20,549 --> 00:29:21,250
It's lovely stuff, huh?

255
00:29:22,231 --> 00:29:26,718
And it's sort of literature, I suppose.

256
00:29:26,837 --> 00:29:27,679
You can call it literature.

257
00:29:28,740 --> 00:29:31,663
And eventually, of course, he won't budge.

258
00:29:34,406 --> 00:29:40,515
And so Mara then approaches him, you see, and he asks him this question.

259
00:29:42,892 --> 00:30:12,527
well let me just read it so now remember all this is being watched by the deities on the ridge of the universe this is a square universe continually raised their heads and craning their necks looked out saying alas ruined indeed is the handsome physical frame of Prince Siddhartha what will he do then the great being told Mara as he stood there claiming the throne accruing on the day of their enlightenment to Bodhisattvas who fulfilled their perfections

260
00:30:12,894 --> 00:30:17,038
Mara, who will testify to your having given away in charity?

261
00:30:18,461 --> 00:30:23,506
Mara stretched forth his hand in the direction of his army, saying, All these are my witnesses.

262
00:30:23,526 --> 00:30:31,674
Instantaneously, the cry of one accord, I am witness, I am his witness, coming from the followers of Mara, resounding like an earthquake.

263
00:30:32,435 --> 00:30:38,261
Then said Mara to the great being, Siddhartha, who will testify to your having given in charity?

264
00:30:39,000 --> 00:30:48,717
And the great being answered, You have sentient beings as witnesses to your having given away in charity, but in this place I have no living being whatever to be my witness.

265
00:30:50,159 --> 00:31:03,000
Let alone the generosity I have practiced in all other existences, let this great and solid earth, non-sentient as it is, be my witness to the seven hundredfold great alms I gave when I was born as Vasantara.

266
00:31:03,672 --> 00:31:17,315
and extricating his right arm from underneath the folds of his robe, he stretched it out towards the earth, saying, Are you or are you not witness of my having given the seven hundredfold arms in my birth as Vesantara?

267
00:31:17,335 --> 00:31:29,375
And the great earth resounded with a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand echoes, as though to overwhelm the forces of Mara, and saying as it were, I was your witness to it then.

268
00:31:33,035 --> 00:31:44,611
Then as the great being continued to reflect on the alms he had given to Vasantara, saying to himself, Oh Siddhartha, you have given away vast charities and made the highest sacrifice.

269
00:31:45,192 --> 00:31:55,026
The elephant Girankala, which is Mara's elephant, which was 150 yoginas in height, went down on its knees.

270
00:31:55,781 --> 00:31:58,064
And the followers of Mara fled in every direction.

271
00:31:58,605 --> 00:32:07,073
No two fled the same path, and they ran in whichever direction that lay before them, discarding their head ornaments and the clothes they were wearing.

272
00:32:12,057 --> 00:32:16,741
So that's the great attack of Mara, put in a metaphorical way.

273
00:32:17,082 --> 00:32:20,065
And of course, those are the hindrances coming.

274
00:32:20,085 --> 00:32:25,029
Those are the final shaking of the self, which doesn't want to come off.

275
00:32:25,599 --> 00:32:28,163
And at root, it's fear, isn't it?

276
00:32:29,987 --> 00:32:35,776
When you get right down to the root emotion of delusion, it's fear.

277
00:32:36,056 --> 00:32:39,781
The fear of the loss of this idea of who I am.

278
00:32:41,344 --> 00:32:42,987
And that's what it's really portraying.

279
00:32:43,007 --> 00:32:44,048
Trying to get across that.

280
00:32:44,328 --> 00:32:47,334
If you just hold your ground, it disappears.

281
00:32:47,673 --> 00:32:48,315
It turns.

282
00:32:48,955 --> 00:32:49,837
It changes.

283
00:32:50,218 --> 00:32:53,182
It just turns into its opposite.

284
00:32:53,202 --> 00:32:54,003
And

285
00:32:54,845 --> 00:33:00,792
What keeps him there, what keeps him able to resist the attack is, of course, his perfections.

286
00:33:01,974 --> 00:33:03,497
Here, of course, it's the charity.

287
00:33:03,978 --> 00:33:17,957
But in our meditation, it's that ability to stand and to observe those reactions that we get when fear arises and to be with it and to allow it to just be there and to get accustomed to fear.

288
00:33:19,018 --> 00:33:24,025
And if we can begin to lose our fear of fear, well...

289
00:33:24,140 --> 00:33:45,759
nothing can frighten us but it's that ability to stand still you see so even though this is a mythological way it's a lovely sort of way of portraying what must be the sort of final death throes of the self that moment when it just disappears so

290
00:33:46,786 --> 00:33:54,454
I'll try and do a bit more of that, go a bit more deeply into the hindrances another time.

291
00:33:55,615 --> 00:34:00,882
But I want to just move on to what happens then.

292
00:34:00,902 --> 00:34:06,587
He, of course, is moving towards the Enlightenment now.

293
00:34:06,607 --> 00:34:14,177
And one of the things that I suppose has always been a little disappointing for me

294
00:34:14,865 --> 00:34:23,496
Because having been brought up in something like Catholicism, which in my experience was a happy religion.

295
00:34:23,516 --> 00:34:25,217
It doesn't go for everybody who is a Catholic.

296
00:34:26,059 --> 00:34:37,211
But also Christians and in the Judaic tradition too, there is this sense of jubilation, this sense of rejoicing and blowing horns and musings.

297
00:34:38,474 --> 00:34:47,601
And when you remember this lovely music, say, of Bach's Alleluia Chorus or Handel's Messiah, you see, and it sort of lifts you, you see.

298
00:34:47,621 --> 00:34:49,744
Well, I always remember Buddha Day.

299
00:34:49,784 --> 00:34:53,168
Now, Buddha Day is, you know, the big, it's the big one.

300
00:34:53,447 --> 00:34:56,510
It's celebrating the founder, you know.

301
00:34:56,670 --> 00:35:06,760
Everything that, even this place is all, this place here now is totally a root dependent on this being that existed 2,500 years ago.

302
00:35:07,516 --> 00:35:09,818
And so one wants to blow horns and hoop a bit, you know.

303
00:35:10,378 --> 00:35:28,478
So on these lovely Buddha days, especially, you know, I'm thinking more, well, it's the same everywhere, but I remember at Kanda Bodha where I was at most of the time, the only difference between Buddha day and everything else was you lined up a bit earlier for food because there was more stuff around.

304
00:35:28,518 --> 00:35:31,061
And that was it.

305
00:35:31,081 --> 00:35:33,804
And then there were these terrible talks and then you went away.

306
00:35:34,423 --> 00:35:35,244
And that was it.

307
00:35:37,164 --> 00:35:49,264
And I want to read out just one more last piece, which at least shows you that in the literature there is this mudita, there is this wonderful sense of rejoicing at this great act.

308
00:35:49,726 --> 00:36:03,088
And I remember I was visiting a very famous monk, he's died now, Ajahn Tate, who used to live on the Thai, right up on the Mekong River there, right up at the top of North Thailand.

309
00:36:03,608 --> 00:36:09,054
And they were building this meditation hall.

310
00:36:09,293 --> 00:36:10,655
I slept in it, actually.

311
00:36:11,516 --> 00:36:18,764
And on the wall, this artist was drawing a depiction of the Enlightenment and a more glorious picture you couldn't have come across.

312
00:36:19,043 --> 00:36:20,626
I mean, it was just full of action.

313
00:36:21,527 --> 00:36:27,253
It was like an exploding star with these beautiful colors.

314
00:36:27,925 --> 00:36:30,887
In a sense, sometimes we forget that.

315
00:36:31,028 --> 00:36:38,978
We forget that actually there's a point where you can actually rejoice and be happy and sort of have a feast.

316
00:36:41,099 --> 00:36:54,355
So here, just before he becomes enlightened, you see, so now the gods know that Mara has been completely routed and the path is completely open for the Bodhisattva.

317
00:36:54,824 --> 00:37:04,956
So the signs go up from one realm to another realm and the whole of the thousand world system is now a gleam, you see.

318
00:37:05,918 --> 00:37:12,164
So the radiance of the banners and streamers hoisted on the eastern ridge of the world sphere spread as far as the western ridge.

319
00:37:12,965 --> 00:37:23,920
Similarly, the radiance of the banners and streamers hoisted on the western ridge, the northern ridge and the southern ridge spread as far as the eastern, southern and northern ridges respectively.

320
00:37:24,675 --> 00:37:38,010
and the radiance of the banners and streamers hoisted on the surface of the earth remained in constant contact with the world of brahma and that those held aloft in the world of brahma penetrated to the very surface of the earth

321
00:37:38,750 --> 00:38:08,367
flowering trees in ten thousand world spheres blossomed forth fruit bearing trees were weighed down with clusters of fruit flowers that bloom on tree trunks branches and creepers blossomed in their respective places lotuses on stalks sprang in clusters of seven breaking through rocky surfaces and were heaped layer upon layer the ten thousand world systems revolved and remained like a wreath of garlands tossed about or like a well-arranged spread of flowers

322
00:38:08,956 --> 00:38:21,840
The intervening regions of 8,000 yojana between the world's spheres, which had not been lit before even by the radiance of seven suns shining together, became one mass of light.

323
00:38:23,003 --> 00:38:27,954
The great ocean, 84,000 yojanas deep, turned into sweet water.

324
00:38:28,775 --> 00:38:30,237
Rivers ceased to flow.

325
00:38:30,472 --> 00:38:33,117
Those blind from birth were able to see objects.

326
00:38:33,556 --> 00:38:36,021
Those deaf from birth were able to hear sounds.

327
00:38:36,081 --> 00:38:38,306
And those crippled from birth walked on their feet.

328
00:38:38,746 --> 00:38:44,456
Bonds and fetters broke loose and fell apart.

329
00:38:44,476 --> 00:38:47,902
So this rejoicing, he now, of course, makes the big breakthrough.

330
00:38:49,164 --> 00:38:54,152
And that's the point of his, what we now call his enlightenment.

331
00:38:55,235 --> 00:38:55,956
And

332
00:38:57,639 --> 00:39:04,568
There's just a little thing here I'd like to say before I leave is religious emotions.

333
00:39:06,452 --> 00:39:10,177
You know, what part do they play in our spiritual life?

334
00:39:10,197 --> 00:39:14,041
Because especially in something like Theravada, you get pretty dry.

335
00:39:15,684 --> 00:39:17,606
Just doing your vipassana.

336
00:39:18,628 --> 00:39:23,934
But that sense of awe that we get, for instance, in the carol Silent Night.

337
00:39:24,943 --> 00:39:32,112
Just to let the story of the Buddha come and just get that sense of awe, the brilliance, the amazing thing.

338
00:39:32,773 --> 00:39:39,739
And then to shift it over to consider the Dharma as an actual living force that runs through the universe.

339
00:39:41,242 --> 00:39:42,923
Praise, adoration.

340
00:39:44,485 --> 00:39:52,875
It's actually one of the objects of jhana meditation is contemplating the Buddha.

341
00:39:53,934 --> 00:39:56,518
You can get, it seems, to first or second jhana with that.

342
00:39:58,481 --> 00:40:01,425
And the sense of rejoicing that we just heard.

343
00:40:02,568 --> 00:40:04,251
To bring that up, a sense of rejoicing.

344
00:40:06,173 --> 00:40:08,277
Then, of course, there's that gratitude.

345
00:40:09,418 --> 00:40:12,342
Just a feeling of that lovely feeling of gratitude.

346
00:40:12,844 --> 00:40:16,108
The more poignant because, you know, this stuff cannot be repaid.

347
00:40:16,188 --> 00:40:19,092
You can't pay the Buddha back for what he did.

348
00:40:20,255 --> 00:40:21,597
In fact, you can't pay anybody back.

349
00:40:21,896 --> 00:40:25,342
That's an idea of paying somebody back.

350
00:40:25,682 --> 00:40:27,925
But just being able to receive the gifts.

351
00:40:27,945 --> 00:40:32,333
And that's why we have this flow of what I call a gift economy.

352
00:40:32,512 --> 00:40:33,293
I read that somewhere.

353
00:40:33,795 --> 00:40:35,438
Where people give each other gifts.

354
00:40:35,797 --> 00:40:38,481
The Dharma and sustenance.

355
00:40:40,224 --> 00:40:41,347
And devotion.

356
00:40:41,927 --> 00:40:44,711
In the morning when I ask people to devote themselves.

357
00:40:44,911 --> 00:40:50,199
Not so much a hard sort of...

358
00:40:50,753 --> 00:40:53,476
a hard sort of giving yourself.

359
00:40:53,536 --> 00:40:55,219
It's more like the heart wants to do it.

360
00:40:55,960 --> 00:40:57,141
You have to cajole yourself.

361
00:40:57,181 --> 00:41:01,007
You have to sort of massage the heart to feel that way.

362
00:41:02,588 --> 00:41:17,690
And one thing that I think especially we in the West have to begin to look at is this whole thing of bowing and what bowing actually means.

363
00:41:18,391 --> 00:41:19,512
Now as you know there are

364
00:41:20,047 --> 00:41:21,048
Many ways to bow.

365
00:41:21,248 --> 00:41:23,150
The Tibetans do a full prostration.

366
00:41:23,831 --> 00:41:28,416
The Theravadans do this bowing like I do when I come in here.

367
00:41:28,996 --> 00:41:32,320
And then there's the Zen which is just bow from the waist.

368
00:41:33,262 --> 00:41:38,847
And then there's just that some people sort of come in and just bow their head.

369
00:41:39,628 --> 00:41:41,911
And then again there's just that blink.

370
00:41:43,152 --> 00:41:47,135
It's just a suggestion of bowing.

371
00:41:47,943 --> 00:41:52,431
So bowing, at first, it always seems a bit strange.

372
00:41:52,490 --> 00:41:55,536
And I remember when I first had to do it in Zen.

373
00:41:55,936 --> 00:41:57,298
I did it because everybody else did it.

374
00:41:58,320 --> 00:42:00,304
But I didn't really get into it for a long time.

375
00:42:02,067 --> 00:42:08,398
And if you think of bowing as a body language, as a way of expressing these types of emotions...

376
00:42:08,833 --> 00:42:12,920
then it's a way of reinforcing the action of the heart.

377
00:42:12,940 --> 00:42:20,070
It's a way of actually giving it a vehicle in which to express these sorts of religious emotions.

378
00:42:21,152 --> 00:42:30,344
And these religious emotions are all bound up and around the faith and the trust and the act of giving oneself to the practice.

379
00:42:30,726 --> 00:42:33,610
There's a sort of the underbelly of it.

380
00:42:34,197 --> 00:42:42,373
Now, of course, to think that they themselves alone get us to be liberated would be a silliness, but they're there as a sort of support.

381
00:42:42,894 --> 00:42:46,782
And some people feel a need for that more than others.

382
00:42:47,523 --> 00:42:54,518
The more intellectual you are, the less you feel you need it, but probably the more you do need it.

383
00:42:56,286 --> 00:43:06,657
And to find a way of expressing that devotion in some sort of body language, I think you'll find very helpful.

384
00:43:08,679 --> 00:43:17,268
The first time I went to Burma to work with Bhujanaka was the only time.

385
00:43:19,070 --> 00:43:25,737
After doing the old hard Mahasi thing in a hall, I got the opportunity to visit Rangoon

386
00:43:26,510 --> 00:43:29,875
And it was difficult to get let out.

387
00:43:30,076 --> 00:43:31,056
You had to have a good reason.

388
00:43:32,199 --> 00:43:35,724
So I gave him the reason that I wanted to buy religious books.

389
00:43:36,485 --> 00:43:43,878
At that time, to get religious books out of the country, you had to go from one government department to the next to get these bits of paper.

390
00:43:44,719 --> 00:43:53,614
The religious department, the censoring department, the export department, and of course I would take a whole day going to see these departments.

391
00:43:54,302 --> 00:43:56,806
and therefore spent the last week wandering around Rangoon.

392
00:43:57,827 --> 00:44:13,630
And walking into the beautiful big pagoda, it's supposed to be one of the seven wonders of the world, the Shwedagon Pagoda, I walked in and I saw these people pouring water over Buddha Rupas and bowing and mumbling.

393
00:44:14,371 --> 00:44:17,094
And I remember distinctly the sentence that came into my head.

394
00:44:17,635 --> 00:44:19,617
It said, well, I'm not a Buddhist.

395
00:44:21,184 --> 00:44:29,237
And that immediate rejection of any form of ritual was almost obedient.

396
00:44:29,536 --> 00:44:35,666
It was cool and cold and like that.

397
00:44:35,847 --> 00:44:48,846
As this whole idea of religious emotions came to me and slowly began to develop, the last time I was in Burma, which was in the year 2000, and I was at Upandita's place,

398
00:44:49,838 --> 00:44:52,702
I had again the opportunity to go to Svetlana Pagoda.

399
00:44:53,664 --> 00:45:02,737
And it's quite remarkable to find myself not quite pouring water over Buddhas, but hanging around this lovely, limpid atmosphere.

400
00:45:03,818 --> 00:45:09,666
And there's a beautiful temple in Sri Lanka called Kelaniya, which is just outside Colombo, if you ever go.

401
00:45:10,427 --> 00:45:13,972
And if you go there on a full moon day,

402
00:45:15,083 --> 00:45:23,032
you can just, you can actually, it's like slicing through butter, the feeling of devotion in the air.

403
00:45:23,574 --> 00:45:25,576
And it's enormously beautiful.

404
00:45:26,376 --> 00:45:31,422
With people just wandering around the Bodhi tree and making their blessings and making their offerings.

405
00:45:32,384 --> 00:45:37,490
And you might say that what it does is it gives a glow to the practice.

406
00:45:38,192 --> 00:45:40,373
It gives a certain glow to it underneath.

407
00:45:41,916 --> 00:45:44,179
And it's something that...

408
00:45:44,632 --> 00:46:12,681
you may consider most people try to do a bit of metta to soften the practice but even these things are very softening and sort of give the practice just that little bit of juice sometimes especially when it gets miserable like the weather we've been having so these things that I've read out are really just examples of how the heart moves sometimes

409
00:46:14,315 --> 00:46:21,682
Buddhism, generally speaking, will always veer towards that more wisdom base because it's centered on knowing.

410
00:46:21,742 --> 00:46:27,148
It's centered on this idea of perception, of discernment.

411
00:46:30,052 --> 00:46:41,385
But these little practices that we can do just put the heart in the right sort of position for it so it moves with that desire to investigate.

412
00:46:51,085 --> 00:47:00,858
So I thought that I would then just read out for you the three sermons which he gave.

413
00:47:01,177 --> 00:47:05,043
Just read them out because they're pretty straightforward.

414
00:47:05,083 --> 00:47:12,893
So remember that when he was enlightened, he left searching for his people.

415
00:47:15,056 --> 00:47:17,920
And I'll come back to that as another lecture.

416
00:47:18,253 --> 00:47:22,960
But on this one here, I'd just like to read the discourse on the turning of the wheel of law.

417
00:47:23,179 --> 00:47:29,369
And I've been a little bit, I've done my own little bit with it so that it reads more smoothly.

418
00:47:29,389 --> 00:47:31,972
Because sometimes it feels stilted.

419
00:47:32,952 --> 00:47:34,074
So this is what I heard.

420
00:47:34,434 --> 00:47:39,362
On one occasion, the Blessed One was dwelling at Benares in the deer park at Isipatana.

421
00:47:39,382 --> 00:47:42,965
And the Blessed One addressed the group of five ascetics, venerable friends.

422
00:47:43,067 --> 00:47:45,730
Yes, venerable friend, those ascetics replied.

423
00:47:46,536 --> 00:47:51,105
Venerable friends, these two extremes should not be practiced by anyone who has entered the spiritual path.

424
00:47:51,425 --> 00:47:55,891
Firstly, the pursuit of happiness in sensual pleasure.

425
00:47:56,373 --> 00:48:00,840
This is low, vulgar, the way of worldlings, ignoble and unbeneficial.

426
00:48:01,722 --> 00:48:06,570
And secondly, the practice of self-mortification, which is ignoble, unbeneficial and painful.

427
00:48:07,612 --> 00:48:11,177
Avoiding these two extremes, the Tathagata has discovered the middle way.

428
00:48:11,597 --> 00:48:19,027
This gives rise to insight, to knowledge, leads to peace, experiential understanding, to enlightenment and nirvana.

429
00:48:19,047 --> 00:48:21,871
And what is this middle way, awakened to by the Tathagata?

430
00:48:22,172 --> 00:48:24,775
It is this noble eightfold path.

431
00:48:24,795 --> 00:48:33,485
Right view, right attitude, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right awareness and right concentration.

432
00:48:34,005 --> 00:48:37,929
Now this, Venerable Friends, is the first noble truth of unsatisfactoriness.

433
00:48:38,190 --> 00:48:39,552
Birth is suffering.

434
00:48:40,391 --> 00:48:41,273
Aging is suffering.

435
00:48:41,333 --> 00:48:42,534
Sickness is suffering.

436
00:48:43,215 --> 00:48:45,117
And being with what we dislike is suffering.

437
00:48:45,436 --> 00:48:47,659
And not being with what we like is suffering.

438
00:48:48,641 --> 00:48:52,384
In fact, not to get what we want is suffering.

439
00:48:52,844 --> 00:49:01,092
In short, the five aggregates of grasping, form, feeling, perceptions, emotion, thoughts, and consciousness are all unsatisfying.

440
00:49:02,507 --> 00:49:13,626
The second noble truth of the cause of unsatisfactoriness is the craving that leads to renewed existence, accompanied by delight and indulgence, seeking happiness here and there.

441
00:49:14,068 --> 00:49:19,436
That is the craving for sensual pleasure, the craving to become, and the craving to annihilate.

442
00:49:20,530 --> 00:49:34,210
And the third noble truth of the cessation of suffering is the fading away without remainder the cessation of that craving, the giving up and relinquishing of that craving and the freedom from it, non-attachment.

443
00:49:34,231 --> 00:49:39,719
The fourth noble truth is the path that leads out of this unsatisfactoriness.

444
00:49:40,847 --> 00:49:56,050
Now, venerable friends, in regard to these understandings that have never been known before, there arose in me the vision, the knowledge, the wisdom, the penetration, and the light, namely, that this is the noble truth of unsatisfactoriness.

445
00:49:56,733 --> 00:50:01,920
This noble truth is to be fully understood, and this noble truth has been fully understood.

446
00:50:03,001 --> 00:50:08,070
This is the noble truth of the cause of unsatisfactoriness.

447
00:50:08,623 --> 00:50:10,947
This noble truth is to be abandoned.

448
00:50:11,528 --> 00:50:13,632
This noble truth has been abandoned.

449
00:50:14,713 --> 00:50:17,759
This is the noble truth of the end of unsatisfactoriness.

450
00:50:18,139 --> 00:50:20,143
And this noble truth is to be realized.

451
00:50:20,682 --> 00:50:22,907
And this noble truth has been realized.

452
00:50:24,128 --> 00:50:27,875
This is the noble truth of the path leading to the end of unsatisfactoriness.

453
00:50:28,376 --> 00:50:30,039
This noble truth is to be developed.

454
00:50:30,619 --> 00:50:32,762
This noble truth has been developed.

455
00:50:33,764 --> 00:50:35,306
So long, venerable sirs.

456
00:50:35,842 --> 00:50:57,106
As my knowledge and vision of these four noble truths, as they really are in their three phases and twelve aspects, was not thoroughly purified in this way, I did not claim to have awakened to the unsurpassed perfect enlightenment in this world with its devas, maras and brahma, in this population with its ascetics and brahmins, its devas and humans.

457
00:50:57,686 --> 00:51:02,711
But now that these noble truths have been fully realized by me, it is so proclaimed.

458
00:51:03,451 --> 00:51:05,954
This is the knowledge and vision arose in me.

459
00:51:06,795 --> 00:51:09,739
Unshakable is the liberation of my citta.

460
00:51:10,541 --> 00:51:12,023
This is my last birth.

461
00:51:12,344 --> 00:51:14,467
There is no more renewed becoming.

462
00:51:15,648 --> 00:51:17,050
This is what the Blessed One said.

463
00:51:17,090 --> 00:51:20,554
And those venerable friends delighted in what he had spoken.

464
00:51:21,115 --> 00:51:28,827
And while the discourse was being delivered, there arose in the venerable Kondanyat the dust-free, stainless vision of the Dharma.

465
00:51:28,847 --> 00:51:32,833
Whatever is subject to arising is all subject to passing away.

466
00:51:33,893 --> 00:51:37,817
And the Blessed One proclaimed, Kandanya knows, Kandanya knows.

467
00:51:38,378 --> 00:51:43,943
And that is how Kandanya earned his name, Anyata Kandanya, the Kandanya who knows.

468
00:51:46,065 --> 00:51:47,927
So that's when he went up and he met with them.

469
00:51:47,967 --> 00:51:55,956
And remember that they first rejected him because they had this feeling that he'd been soft and gone off and eaten rice pudding.

470
00:51:57,516 --> 00:51:58,297
And that was the limit.

471
00:51:59,003 --> 00:52:02,547
So when he went back, they didn't particularly like him coming.

472
00:52:02,606 --> 00:52:04,929
They thought, well, he's coming to tempt us.

473
00:52:04,949 --> 00:52:12,317
But in fact, it seems as though they were so taken by the way he looked that they were prepared to sit down and discuss these things with him.

474
00:52:13,998 --> 00:52:16,922
These things, of course, these scriptures were written after the event.

475
00:52:18,583 --> 00:52:20,746
So then they all went off to get their arms around.

476
00:52:20,786 --> 00:52:25,652
On the way back, having eaten their arms around, they all sat down and he gave them another talk.

477
00:52:26,492 --> 00:52:28,554
And this one is the characteristic of not-self.

478
00:52:30,442 --> 00:52:31,422
This is what I heard.

479
00:52:31,483 --> 00:52:36,570
On one occasion, the Blessed One was dwelling at Benares in the deer park at Isipetana.

480
00:52:36,590 --> 00:52:40,817
And there the Blessed One addressed a group of five ascetics, venerable friends.

481
00:52:41,338 --> 00:52:43,380
Yes, venerable friend, the ascetics replied.

482
00:52:44,242 --> 00:52:45,603
Form is not self.

483
00:52:46,724 --> 00:52:49,849
If form were self, then it would not lead to affliction.

484
00:52:51,010 --> 00:52:53,155
And it would be possible to determine form.

485
00:52:53,574 --> 00:52:55,378
Let my form be like this.

486
00:52:55,797 --> 00:52:57,681
Let my form not be like this.

487
00:52:58,572 --> 00:53:04,320
It would be the same with feelings, perceptions, emotions, and thoughts, and even consciousness itself.

488
00:53:04,681 --> 00:53:11,472
If consciousness were self, we would be able to say, let my consciousness be like this, let it not be like this.

489
00:53:13,213 --> 00:53:16,259
Now I ask you, is form permanent or impermanent?

490
00:53:16,800 --> 00:53:18,242
Impermanent, venerable friend.

491
00:53:19,123 --> 00:53:22,789
And whatever is impermanent, is that satisfying or unsatisfying?

492
00:53:22,809 --> 00:53:25,052
It does not satisfy, venerable sir.

493
00:53:26,061 --> 00:53:34,818
And is that which is impermanent, does not satisfy, and is subject to change, to be regarded as, this is me, this is mine, this is myself?

494
00:53:35,521 --> 00:53:38,266
Not at all, Venerable Friend.

495
00:53:38,286 --> 00:53:43,536
Can we not say the same of feelings, perceptions, emotions, and thoughts, and even consciousness itself?

496
00:53:44,157 --> 00:53:47,344
Indeed, Venerable Friend, replied the five ascetics.

497
00:53:48,657 --> 00:54:06,262
So it follows that any kind of form whatsoever, whether past, future or present, internal or external, gross or subtle, inferior or superior, far or near, all form is to be correctly regarded as, this is not me, this is not mine, this is not myself.

498
00:54:07,344 --> 00:54:13,331
And the same goes for feelings, perceptions, emotions, thoughts and even consciousness itself.

499
00:54:15,302 --> 00:54:29,802
Now, venerable friends, when someone who has heard this understands in this way, they become disenchanted with form, disenchanted with feelings and perceptions, disenchanted with emotions and thoughts, disenchanted even with consciousness itself.

500
00:54:30,842 --> 00:54:33,606
And once disenchanted, they become dispassionate.

501
00:54:34,086 --> 00:54:37,030
And through this detachment, the citta is liberated.

502
00:54:37,791 --> 00:54:40,956
And when liberated, it realizes this is liberation.

503
00:54:41,677 --> 00:54:51,907
And they come to know birth is no more, the spiritual life has been fulfilled, what had to be done has been done, there is no more returning to any state of becoming.

504
00:54:54,110 --> 00:54:58,875
This is what the Blessed One said, and those venerable friends delighted in what he had spoken.

505
00:54:59,815 --> 00:55:08,445
And while this discourse is being delivered, the chitter of those group of five ascetics were liberated from the floods of non-clinging.

506
00:55:10,146 --> 00:55:13,110
So now we've got five Arahats in the world.

507
00:55:14,733 --> 00:55:17,076
And I'd like to read this one too.

508
00:55:17,335 --> 00:55:18,918
It's also a little short one.

509
00:55:18,938 --> 00:55:19,818
Well, I've made it short.

510
00:55:21,320 --> 00:55:22,382
I'm taking all the repetitions.

511
00:55:22,762 --> 00:55:25,706
This is the one that T.S.

512
00:55:25,746 --> 00:55:26,768
Eliot writes.

513
00:55:26,788 --> 00:55:29,130
And it's in his poem somewhere.

514
00:55:29,152 --> 00:55:32,755
And it's the one where he's describing burning.

515
00:55:32,956 --> 00:55:37,302
And here he's talking to a thousand monks.

516
00:55:38,902 --> 00:55:39,844
This is what I heard.

517
00:55:40,164 --> 00:55:45,255
This is not so, you know, I mean, in the story this happens very shortly after his enlightenment.

518
00:55:46,117 --> 00:55:47,018
This is what I heard.

519
00:55:47,139 --> 00:55:52,449
On one occasion, the Blessed One was dwelling at Gaia, at Gaia's head, together with a thousand monks.

520
00:55:53,210 --> 00:55:56,697
And there the Blessed One gave this discourse to them.

521
00:55:56,717 --> 00:55:57,659
All is burning.

522
00:55:58,422 --> 00:56:00,606
And what is this all that is burning?

523
00:56:00,771 --> 00:56:15,641
It is the eye that is burning, forms are burning, eye consciousness is burning, eye contact is burning, and whatever feeling is conditioned by that eye contact, whether it be pleasant, unpleasant, or neither pleasant nor unpleasant, that too is burning.

524
00:56:16,668 --> 00:56:31,099
burning with what burning with the fires of craving the fires of aversion the fires of delusion burning with birth aging sickness and death burning with sorrow pain desolation and despair

525
00:56:32,681 --> 00:56:37,528
And so it is with all the senses, with hearing, tasting, smelling and touching.

526
00:56:37,548 --> 00:56:51,889
And the mind itself is also burning, burning with the fires of craving, the fires of aversion, the fires of delusion, burning with birth, aging, sickness and death, burning with sorrow, pain, desolation and despair.

527
00:56:53,572 --> 00:57:18,976
Now when a meditator, properly instructed, grasps this by direct experience, they become disenchanted with the eye, disenchanted with forms, disenchanted with eye consciousness, disenchanted with eye contact, and disenchanted with whatever feeling is conditioned by that eye contact, whether it be pleasant, unpleasant, or neither pleasant nor unpleasant.

528
00:57:18,996 --> 00:57:22,398
And so it is with all the senses and the very mind itself.

529
00:57:23,407 --> 00:57:29,376
Once disenchanted with the sensual world as a source of happiness, the meditator loses interest.

530
00:57:29,978 --> 00:57:32,681
And through this dispassion, they become liberated.

531
00:57:33,382 --> 00:57:35,545
And with that liberation there comes this knowledge.

532
00:57:36,106 --> 00:57:37,690
There will be no more birth.

533
00:57:38,150 --> 00:57:40,152
The spiritual life has been fulfilled.

534
00:57:40,693 --> 00:57:42,597
What had to be done has been done.

535
00:57:43,038 --> 00:57:46,463
There will be no more returning into states of becoming.

536
00:57:48,367 --> 00:57:50,050
That is what the Blessed One said.

537
00:57:50,090 --> 00:57:53,875
Elated those monks, delighted in the Blessed One's teachings.

538
00:57:54,416 --> 00:58:05,313
And while this discourse was being delivered, the hearts of those thousand monks were liberated from the tents through the way of non-clinging.

539
00:58:05,333 --> 00:58:07,775
So, just to...

540
00:58:08,016 --> 00:58:11,442
Sometimes I think we don't read the scriptures enough, you know.

541
00:58:11,461 --> 00:58:16,128
So, I just want to bring this to an end by...

542
00:58:18,387 --> 00:58:31,242
just going back to his victory verse, and then I shall chant it in Pali, and we'll sit for a while, a bit of silence, and then we'll do the metta.

543
00:58:33,204 --> 00:58:46,621
So now he's fully enlightened, he's broken through, he's awakened, and this is the victory verse that he told Ananda that sprung spontaneously to him upon that awakening.

544
00:58:47,260 --> 00:58:54,028
Seeking but not finding the house-builder, I have travelled from birth to birth countless times.

545
00:58:54,710 --> 00:58:58,114
Painful indeed is birth over and over again.

546
00:58:59,215 --> 00:59:02,521
But now, O house-builder, you have been seen.

547
00:59:03,202 --> 00:59:05,083
You shall not build another house again.

548
00:59:05,164 --> 00:59:09,550
Your rafters have been broken, your ridgepole demolished.

549
00:59:10,972 --> 00:59:16,659
My citta has attained the unconditioned and gone beyond any kind of craving.

550
00:59:20,791 --> 00:59:30,382
Aneka jati sansarang, sandawesang anibisang, gahakaraka gawesanto dukha jati punapunang.

551
00:59:31,322 --> 00:59:41,175
Gahakaraka ditozi, punagehang nakahazi, sabate pasukabaga gahakutan visankatan.

552
00:59:42,115 --> 00:59:47,322
Visankaragatan chitan, tananan kaya majjaga.

